accesses.location: No boats allowed. Pier and shore fishing areas are available.

surveys.narrative: Cenaiko Lake is a designated stream trout lake located in the Coon Rapids Dam Regional Park. Trout are stocked annually to provide a unique fishing opportunity in the Twin Cites Metro Area. Heavy fishing pressure is common when the trout season opens. Winter angling is very popular, especially on opening weekend. Brown trout were found in low abundance during this assessment. This is not unexpected due to the popularity of the fishery. Hybrid sunfish were the most abundant species sampled, but the fish were small. Bluegills were captured for the first time in trap nets in this lake. Bluegills were seined during the 2003 survey but their presence in the trap nets indicated the population is growing. Black crappies were uncommon while white crappies were more numerous, but are small.

THE TROUT POPULATION WAS NOT ASSESSED ADEQUATELY WITH TRAP NETS (SHORELINE TOO STEEP IN MOST AREAS) HOWEVER, ANGLER REPORTS OF AN EXCELLENT CATCH OF TROUT INDICATES THAT THE FISH ARE THRIVING WITHIN THE TIME FRAME OF A LAKE FISHERY. THE OCCURRENCE OF A FEW CARP AND BLH, ALONG WITH MANY HSF WOULD BE DISCOURAGING EXCEPT FOR THE FACT THAT MOST OF THE LAKE IS DEEP AND COOL AND NOT LIKELY TO BE OVERRUN BY COMPETING WARM WATER SPECIES TO THE DETRIMENT OF TROUT.

Brook trout were sampled in low numbers in this population assessment. All fish appeared to be from the surplus broodstock stocking in January, 1998. Black bullhead and white sucker dominated the catch with all fish small in size. Carp were present in moderate numbers with most small. White crappie and hybrid sunfish were present with some large individuals. Smallmouth bass were moderately abundant with all fish captured under 10 inches in length.

Cenaiko Lake is a designated stream trout lake located in the Coon Rapids Dam Regional Park. Rainbow trout and brook trout have been stocked annually. Heavy fishing pressure is common when the trout seasons open. Winter angling is very popular, especially opening weekend. Brook trout were found in low abundance during this survey, most likely due to the popularity of the fishery. Hybrid sunfish were the most abundant species sampled, but the fish were small. White crappies were found in average abundance, but were also small. Some of the fish did exceed 10 inches, but they were rare. Carp were present in low numbers. The black bullhead catch was down overall from previous surveys.
